                  is the log likelihood under the alternative. This statistic is distributed as χ2with degrees of freedom equal to the number of restrictions under the null hypothesis (in this case, equals one). Clearly, the LR statistics presented intable 1are well above the critical value at the 1%, thereby rejecting the normality of extremes.

The LR test statistic is calculated as
                     \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $\mathrm{LR}\,=2n[ \mathrm{ln}\,( \mathrm{S.E.R}\,^{*}) -\mathrm{ln}\,( \mathrm{S.E.R.}\,) ] ,$ \end{document}
                  wherenis the number of observations, S.E.R* is the standard error of regression of the restricted model (such as the Gumbel or the exponential distribution), and S.E.R. is the standard error of regression of the unrestricted model (such as the GEV or the GPD). This statistic is distributed as the chi‐squared with 1 degree of freedom.

sec.p:
We run a Monte Carlo experiment to provide supporting evidence for the extreme value approach to calculating VaR. Following the recent literature developed by Ait‐Sahalia (1996a
            ,1996b
            ), Conley et al. (1997), and Stanton (1997), we specify the drift and diffusion of the interest rate process as a nonlinear function of the short rate level. More specifically, we assume that the short‐term interest rate is the solution to a stochastic differential equation of the form19

fn.p:
Chan et al. (1992) propose a one‐factor interest rate model that specifies a linear mean‐reverting drift,
                     \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $\mu ( r_{t}) =\alpha _{0}+\alpha _{1}r_{t},$ \end{document}
                  and a constant elasticity of variance for the diffusion function,
                     \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $\sigma ( r_{t}) =\sigma r^{\gamma }_{t}.$ \end{document}
                  Although the Chan et al. model encompasses a wide variety of well‐known models, it is rejected against the more flexible models with highly nonlinear functional forms for the drift and diffusion functions. These nonlinear short‐rate specifications are introduced by Ait‐Sahalia (1996a
                  ,1996b
                  ), Conley et al. (1997), and Stanton (1997).

